Certainly! Here's an example of how you can create an HTML website with a custom background image, a placeholder for an image, and a list of 4 steps:

```
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
	<title>My Website</title>
	<style>
		body {
			background-image: url('path/to/background-image.jpg');
			background-size: cover;
			background-position: center;
			font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
			text-align: center;
			color: white;
		}

		.image-placeholder {
			width: 300px;
			height: 300px;
			background-color: #ccc;
			display: inline-block;
			margin-top: 20px;
		}

		h1 {
			margin-top: 40px;
		}

		ul {
			list-style: none;
			padding: 0;
			margin-top: 40px;
		}

		li {
			margin: 10px 0;
		}
	</style>
</head>
<body>
	<h1>Welcome to My Website</h1>
	<div class="image-placeholder"></div>
	<ul>
		<li>Step 1: Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit.</li>
		<li>Step 2: Duis dapibus eros in nibh malesuada, non interdum ante porta.</li>
		<li>Step 3: Vivamus tincidunt massa a eleifend pellentesque.</li>
		<li>Step 4: Sed in quam ornare, bibendum magna in, tempor elit.</li>
	</ul>
</body>
</html>
```

In the CSS block, we've added some styles to create a background image for the page using the `background-image` property. We've also created a class called `.image-placeholder` to add a gray placeholder box that you can replace with your own image. The `<h1>` element displays a welcome message, and the `<ul>` element lists the 4 steps with some margin added for spacing. You can replace the text of the steps with your own content.

To change the background image, replace `path/to/background-image.jpg` with the path to the image file on your local device. To replace the placeholder image, you can add an `<img>` element inside the `.image-placeholder` div. For example:

```
<div class="image-placeholder">
	<img src="path/to/image.jpg" alt="My Image">
</div>
```

Replace `path/to/image.jpg` with the path to your desired placeholder image.
